title: For Sale:  Henry Big Boy Eagle Scout Centennial 44 Mag H006ES
postcontent:
This is a brand new in box Henry Repeating Big Boy Eagle Scout Centennial Edition lever-action rifle chambered for .44 Magnum. It is also capable of firing .44 Special. To showcase the Eagle Scout's historic milestone, each Henry Big Boy Eagle Scout Centennial Edition rifle is etched with the Eagle Scout Award Medal and selectively nickel plated on the right side of the receiver with an American style scroll pattern bracketing the medal and the banner with the words "THIS I PLEDGE MY SACRED HONOR." These words are the closing line of the pledge that is recited to every Eagle Scout at his Eagle Court of Honor as a reminder of what has been achieved and what is promised. A black fill is baked into the side of the brass receiver to highlight the medal, scroll, banner and text

On the left side of the receiver is etched the Official BSA Eagle Scout 100th Anniversary commemorative logo which is selectively nickeled plated. Also etched and black filled into the receiver are the American scroll pattern and a banner with the words "BOY SCOUTS OF AMERICA." Into the right side of the American walnut stock is laser etched and hand painted in multiple colors rendering of a soaring eagle, a Bald Eagle with an enduring gaze, and the words "ONCE AN EAGLE ALWAYS AN EAGLE" an iconic expression that reminds Eagle Scouts that the spirit of the Eagle Scout Award is one demonstrated with honor and conviction throughout their life. On the forearm's right side are four Eagle Scout badges laser scrimshaw style into the American Walnut wood and hand painted in a nickel coloring. These badges represent the design changes of the badge over its 100 year history.

This Special Edition Big Boy is operated by Henry's venerable Lever Action. Weight is about 8.7 pounds, and it has a fully adjustable Marbles semi-buckhorn rear sight and brass beaded front sight. The receiver is polished brass and the octagonal barrel and lever loop are blued. The furniture is American Walnut and the barrel and lever are Blued. The receiver is drilled and tapped to attach a sight base if desired. This beautiful Henry Rifle is Made in America.

title: For Sale:  Virginian Dragoon .44 mag Revolver
postcontent:
I have two for sale. One is Stainless with a 7 1/2 inch barrel-walnut grips for 550.00 and the other Virginian Dragoon, six shooter, 6 inch blued barrel. Both are perhaps in my view one of the finest single action revolvers ever made. These were manufactured in Alexandria, Virginia. The Hitchner Corporation cast a heavy revolver frame using 4140 Steel, app. 10% more substantial than its contemporaries- Ruger Blackhawk and S&W. These Dragoon revolvers  were built to very close tolerances and hand fitted and individually tuned and lock up tighter than almost any other single action ever made, similar to the individual quality of the colt line of Pythons. The large bolt and cylinder stops contribute greatly to these quality features. A Swiss Safety was incorporated into the design along with cylinder dots drilled to the left and right of one bore to indicate the empty chamber, also quite unique to the Dragoon. The revolver has adjustable rear sights with walnut grips that show no sign of wear. 
Other features include one piece back strap, brazed front sight, recessed cylinders, coil mainspring, internal firing pin, split grip panels, and unlike Ruger, Interarms used a locked firing pin busing on the Dragoon. The list price in the early 80's when this was made was 280.00 whereas the Blackhawk, 10% less substantial in structure, was only 200.00. The cost of hand fitting and tuning each one of these Dragoons individually along with other excellent unique features left the Dragoon at a price point of $80.00 above the MSRP of the Blackhawk. These extras put an impact on the overall sales of the Dragoon and production was haulted in 1985. 
These Dragoon revolvers are considered by many to be 'sleepers' in that year by year the demand for these and appreciation for their quality engineering and craftsmanship continues to drive the price upward. It's a fantastic .44 caliber and great investment in a large bore revolver. You will not be a bit disappointed. 
If shipped, the buyer pays the app. 25.00 shipping costs and FFL fees on the receiving end if applicable. The revolver must be shipped FFL to FFL paid by USPS Postal Check or purchased in person. Both are priced to sell at a time when excellent quality .44 revolver handguns -reasonably priced -are almost impossible to find. 
Photos upon request.
